Interview:
To create and connect to an EC2 instance, I launch an instance from the AWS console, configure security groups and key pairs, and then use SSH with the private key to securely connect to the instance.

Step 1: Launch EC2 Instance in Amazon Web Services
Steps:
1a. Go to AWS Console → EC2
1b. Click Launch Instance
1c. Choose AMI (e.g., Ubuntu or Amazon Linux)
1d. Choose instance type (t2.micro – free tier)
1e. Create/select Key Pair (.pem file)
1f. Configure Security Group:
1g. Allow SSH (Port 22) from your IP
1h. Click Launch

Step 2: Prepare Key File (on your local machine)
bash
chmod 400 key.pem

This secures your private key (required for SSH)

Step 3: Connect to EC2 Instance (SSH)
3a. Click on Connect
3b. ssh -i mykey.pem ubuntu@3.250.xxx.xxx (to connect the instance on local machine)

Step 4: Verify Connection
Once connected, you’ll see:

bash
ubuntu@ip-xxx:~$

Now you are inside your EC2 Linux server

Tip:
In real projects:

Use SSH + automation scripts
Or use AWS Systems Manager for secure access without opening port 22
